\taxon{Definition}
\title{Mixing coefficient}
\p{
  Let #{x_t} be a stochastic process, which we identify with a measure on #{X^\RR} for some #{X}. Let #{F_a^b} denote the #{\sigma}-algebra on this space generated by #{\pi_t} for #{t \in [a,b]} (so that #{F_{-\infty}^t} is the natural filtration). Then the \em{strong mixing coefficient} is the function
  ##{\alpha(s) = \sup \{P(A)P(B) - P(A \cap B) \mid A \in F_{-\infty}^a, B \in F_{a+s}^\infty, a \in \RR\}}, the greatest failure of events separated by time #{s} to be independent. The process is strongly mixing if #{\alpha(s) \to 0}.
}